statutePage.section2Text:
2.1. The main purpose of the Association is to promote entrepreneurship in Ukraine, protect the legal rights and interests of its members, and develop international economic cooperation.

2.2. Main objectives of the Association:
— uniting entrepreneurs for collective protection of professional interests;
— representing members' interests in relations with state authorities and local self-government bodies;
— facilitating the integration of Ukrainian business into the international economic community;
— organizing and conducting conferences, forums, seminars, and trainings;
— developing mentorship and educational programs for entrepreneurs;
— supporting innovation and digital business transformation;
— facilitating investment attraction into the Ukrainian economy.

2.3. To achieve its statutory goals, the Association has the right to:
— enter into agreements and contracts;
— establish committees, working groups, and temporary commissions;
— found enterprises, institutions, and organizations;
— conduct publishing activities;
— carry out international activities and establish partnerships.

statutePage.section3Text:
3.1. Membership in the Association is voluntary, individual, and free of charge. Admission is based exclusively on the candidate's entrepreneurial achievements.

3.2. The following may become members of the Association:
— individual entrepreneurs who have reached 18 years of age and have at least 2 years of confirmed entrepreneurial experience;
— legal entities — business entities that have been operating for at least 2 years.

3.3. Mandatory admission requirements:
— impeccable business reputation;
— adherence to ethical business standards;
— recommendation from two current members of the Association or partner organizations;
— willingness to actively participate in the Association's activities.

3.4. Admission procedure:
— the candidate submits a written application describing entrepreneurial achievements;
— the Council conducts an interview with the candidate;
— the admission decision is made by the Council by simple majority within 30 calendar days;
— in case of rejection, the candidate may reapply after 6 months.

3.5. Membership is terminated in the following cases:
— voluntary withdrawal based on a written statement;
— expulsion for violation of the Statute or Code of Ethics (by 2/3 vote of the Council);
— liquidation of the legal entity member;
— death of the individual member;
— systematic non-participation in the Association's activities for 12 months without valid reasons.

statutePage.section4Text:
4.1. Members of the Association have the right to:
— participate in the management of the Association through the General Assembly;
— elect and be elected to governing and supervisory bodies;
— submit proposals to the General Assembly agenda;
— receive information about the Association's activities and financial status;
— use the services, resources, and infrastructure of the Association;
— participate in events, programs, and projects of the Association;
— use the Association's symbols in the established manner;
— appeal decisions of the governing bodies;
— freely withdraw from the Association at their own discretion.

statutePage.section5Text:
5.1. Members of the Association are obligated to:
— comply with the provisions of this Statute and the Association's Code of Ethics;
— fulfill decisions of the General Assembly, Council, and other governing bodies;
— actively contribute to achieving statutory goals;
— refrain from actions that harm the interests and reputation of the Association;
— notify the Council of changes to contact information within 10 business days;
— share professional experience and participate in mentorship programs;
— maintain high standards of business ethics in their own entrepreneurial activities.

statutePage.section6Text:
6.1. The General Assembly is the supreme governing body of the Association.

6.2. The General Assembly is convened at least once a year. Extraordinary General Assemblies are convened at the request of the Council, the Audit Commission, or at least 1/3 of the Association's members.

6.3. The General Assembly has a quorum if more than half of the Association's members are present. Remote participation is permitted.

6.4. The exclusive competence of the General Assembly includes:
— approval of and amendments to the Statute;
— election and recall of the President, Council members, and Audit Commission;
— approval of the Council's annual report and Audit Commission conclusions;
— determining strategic areas of activity;
— deciding on reorganization or liquidation of the Association;
— reviewing member complaints about Council decisions.

6.5. Decisions of the General Assembly are adopted by simple majority of those present, except for matters requiring a qualified majority (2/3 of votes): amendments to the Statute, liquidation, reorganization.

statutePage.section7Text:
7.1. The Council is the collegial governing body that operates between General Assemblies.

7.2. The Council consists of 7–15 members elected by the General Assembly for a term of 3 years. The same person may not hold a Council position for more than two consecutive terms.

7.3. Council meetings are held at least once a month. Decisions are made by simple majority of members present.

7.4. The Council's powers include:
— admitting and expelling members of the Association;
— approving the annual budget and monitoring its execution;
— establishing committees, working groups, and temporary commissions;
— approving event plans and activity programs;
— making personnel decisions regarding the executive staff;
— managing the Association's property and funds;
— preparing reports for the General Assembly.

statutePage.section8Text:
8.1. The President is the highest-ranking official, elected by the General Assembly for a term of 3 years.

8.2. The President:
— represents the Association in relations with third parties, state authorities, and international organizations;
— chairs the General Assembly and Council meetings;
— signs documents on behalf of the Association;
— acts on behalf of the Association without a power of attorney;
— bears personal responsibility for the Association's activities;
— reports to the General Assembly.

8.3. In the temporary absence of the President, their powers are exercised by the Vice-President or another Council member by Council decision.

statutePage.section9Text:
9.1. The Audit Commission is a supervisory body elected by the General Assembly consisting of 3 members for a term of 3 years.

9.2. Audit Commission members may not simultaneously serve as Council members or hold other positions in the Association.

9.3. The Audit Commission:
— exercises control over the financial and economic activities of the Association;
— reviews the annual report and balance sheet;
— monitors compliance with the Statute by governing bodies;
— submits conclusions to the General Assembly;
— has the right to demand an extraordinary convocation of the General Assembly if significant violations are discovered.

statutePage.section10Text:
10.1. To implement specific areas of activity, the Council has the right to establish permanent committees and temporary working groups.

10.2. Permanent committees are established for main areas:
— Committee on International Cooperation;
— Committee on Education and Development;
— Committee on Advocacy and Interest Protection;
— Committee on Innovation and Digital Transformation;
— Ethics Committee.

10.3. Committee chairs are appointed by the Council from among Association members for a term of 2 years.

10.4. Committees operate on the basis of regulations approved by the Council and report to the Council quarterly.

statutePage.section11Text:
11.1. Members of the Association are obligated to comply with the Code of Ethics approved by the Council.

11.2. Core principles of the Code of Ethics:
— integrity and transparency in business conduct;
— rejection of corrupt practices and unfair competition;
— respect for the rights of employees, counterparties, and consumers;
— compliance with legislation and international standards;
— corporate social responsibility;
— confidentiality of information received within the Association's activities.

11.3. Violations of the Code of Ethics are reviewed by the Ethics Committee and may serve as grounds for a warning or expulsion from the Association.

statutePage.section12Text:
12.1. The Association is a non-profit organization. The Association's income is not subject to distribution among its members.

12.2. Sources of the Association's property and funds include:
— voluntary donations and charitable contributions from individuals and legal entities;
— grants from international organizations and foundations;
— sponsorship support;
— income from events, conferences, and educational programs;
— income from entrepreneurial activities directed toward achieving statutory goals;
— other receipts not prohibited by law.

12.3. Membership in the Association is free of charge. No membership fees are collected.

12.4. The Association's funds are used exclusively to achieve statutory goals and objectives.

12.5. The Association maintains accounting and tax records in accordance with Ukrainian legislation. The fiscal year coincides with the calendar year.

statutePage.section13Text:
13.1. The Association conducts international activities in accordance with Ukrainian legislation.

13.2. The Association has the right to:
— establish and maintain partnerships with foreign and international organizations;
— join international associations and unions;
— open representative offices abroad in accordance with established legal procedures;
— organize international business missions, forums, and conferences;
— facilitate export activities of Association members.

13.3. The Association's representative offices abroad operate on the basis of regulations approved by the Council.
